textDisplay: A seven is generous. More like a six at best and I say that as a fan of .Paak and Bruno. This one is tacky and far too polished. It's great that they're pushing funk and soul in the mainstream, and this might be the gateway for kids to get into an incredible era of music, but this just doesn't compare to the classics. This is like the Robocop remake compared to the OG. Not nearly raw enough. Peep Madlib's "Black Soul" mixtape or any P-Funk instead.
textOriginal: A seven is generous. More like a six at best and I say that as a fan of .Paak and Bruno. This one is tacky and far too polished. It's great that they're pushing funk and soul in the mainstream, and this might be the gateway for kids to get into an incredible era of music, but this just doesn't compare to the classics. This is like the Robocop remake compared to the OG. Not nearly raw enough. Peep Madlib's "Black Soul" mixtape or any P-Funk instead.

textDisplay: Why are you lot complaining about this score? It's obviously a good score, A, and B, it's not a revolutionary album. It's fine, it's highly listenable, slick, and fun, but don't get it twisted: this record is pop schmooze, it's not some kind of artistic world-changer. It's kitsch of the highest quality, but kitsch all the same, totally unoriginal and commercialised. It's a good record, and sounds dope, it's not a 10 or some bullshit like that, cause it doesn't break new ground, it just polishes old ground.
textOriginal: Why are you lot complaining about this score? It's obviously a good score, A, and B, it's not a revolutionary album. It's fine, it's highly listenable, slick, and fun, but don't get it twisted: this record is pop schmooze, it's not some kind of artistic world-changer. textDisplay:
I feel like most people who are losing their minds over this album and this review have probably never listened to classic soul music before. The whole selling point of the album is that they're impersonating a very specific style and aesthetic that has existed for decades and probably hit its creative peak already long ago. And for the most part, they execute the music they're attempting to emulate really well here, but never really take it anywhere interesting. At various points during the album the intention of emulation becomes so obvious that the instrumentals begin to sound a little soulless (ironically), and if it wasn't for Bruno and Anderson's charisma on vocals, you would feel as if you're listening to any youtube free to use "type track". Almost as some kind of "genre-cosplay" (I think Melon described it really well here).

It's a good album, but it doesn't deserve more than a 7 in my opinion.

And for the most part, they execute the music they're attempting to emulate really well here, but never really take it anywhere interesting. At various points during the album the intention of emulation becomes so obvious that the instrumentals begin to sound a little soulless (ironically), and if it wasn't for Bruno and Anderson's charisma on vocals, you would feel as if you're listening to any youtube free to use "type track". It's a good album, but it doesn't deserve more than a 7 in my opinion.

textDisplay:
My opinions on the album:
The unexpected combination of R&B, Smooth Soul, Funk, and melodic pop were all inserted into their debut record to make an undisputedly fascinating nostalgic album, sucking influences from the late 70s to early 80s music. The transitional creativity of the percussion and mind-out-of-body vocalisation was astonishingly well-executed as the chemistry between Anderson and Bruno Mars proved to be an intuitive experience. The narrative seemed to get into a downward relationship story that detailed a one-sided love story from the point of view of Bruno and Anderson. Whilst every track on the record may not be relevant to the narrative, instrumentally speaking, the thematic genre-blending experience seemed to make parallels with the classic 2019 release, "Igor". The melodic approach to most tracks appeared to turn into a near-perfect experience for me as well. The supreme songwriting and competent vocal ranges by both artists of the duo created an overall entertainment paradise. The most recognizable and acknowledged part of the record is how the instrumentation is raw and basic, yet it feels so complex due to the heavy vocalisations, this is a historic debut and will go down as one of the most fascinating debuts, I reckon.
9/10
(This was a review I wrote on RYM btw)

textDisplay: This is the first time I've felt the need to comment melon, but I couldn't disagree with you more on this one. This album is pure joy, and it's short length and consistent sound for me is not a valid criticism to bring it to a 7. Every song has its unique parts and the musicianship is at such a high quality that for me it doesn't feel 'repetitive' in the slightest- that would be like dissing 'is this it?' by the strokes just cos it keeps to the same sound. Also the shortness criticism does not work: for one, you seem to imply that they kept it this short because if it had been longer the sound would wear thin- but it isn't longer, so therefore this is more of a hypothesis than an actual criticism. And for two, you have given other short albums (ie kids see ghosts) a higher score before. Idk man, I love this album and expected you too as well, considering your reactions to a few of the songs prior to this review.

textDisplay: When I first heard this album, for some reason I immediately thought of Michael Jacksons “Got to Be There” album especially the song “Ain’t no sunshine” I personally give this album a 7 to light 8. There is 3 strong songs on there but the rest will probably be forgettable in time to come. It’s a great album but I think that are many in shock listening to this because they never really heard soul music into the mainstream. There is many 60s/ 70s soul albums that great in vocals, production, even better lyrics, and etc. This album was like a nostalgic throwback. They did it well. But this album sure does remind me of Stevie Wonder, The Jackson 5, and many more.

textDisplay: I don't think a genre revival should be discussed as a lack of creativity or innovation. Music isn't evolving in a single direction - coming back to these genres that fell out of favor is a new opportunity to incorporate different techniques together, which is what they do very well on this record. This is very much a love letter to the 70s, but in no way are they just recording a cover album. A nostalgic tone doesn't make the music less unique.
textOriginal: I don't think a genre revival should be discussed as a lack of creativity or innovation. textDisplay:
This album an 8. The songs that hit hit so fucking hard that even weaker songs, which are still really good, also appear golden. On a first listen it feels like a 9-10 just because you’re left on such a high from some of the songs and as well specific moments from songs. After listening to it a ton and sitting on it for a bit the cracks start forming. Still though, on every track you can feel the joy that was had making this album shining brightly through to the point that you’re smiling along the whole way. It’s just so deeply endearing and charming that it’s impossible to hate any track even if it might not stick with you for as long as others might. You can also tell just how skilled Andy and Bruno are as musicians throughout the whole project. Andersons drumming is fucking impeccable. You can tell a skilled, passionate drummer was involved in every song cause, as a drummer myself, it’s a dream to listen to. Not to mention the production. Holy shit. The drums sound fucking beautiful on this album, this the ideal way for drums to sound.

Yeah just some rambling thoughts. Curious what other people think lmk

textDisplay: I’m relieved to hear somebody not totally eat this album up and overlook its shortcomings. This is definitely a solid project but I don’t foresee it standing the test of time. The majority of the tracks feel like spoofs of soul from the seventies, biting a little too heavily on all of those artists you mentioned. The other aspect I found to make even the first listen a bit dull was the frequent recycling of rhythmic phrases and arrangements from within the album itself. Before any new section, just about every single track had some sort of syncopated breakdown coupled with stark chord changes and immediately followed by a long drum fill. But I digress; I think a seven out of ten is a fair, kind score for fresh impressions. Give it some time though, I don’t predict this album getting any more enjoyable—just more stale and forgettable.

textDisplay:
I’d say the album was way too short. 4/9 the songs released as singles and they were easily the best songs. Fly as me was ok but the spelling part felt awkward and there was barely any Bruno on the song. Didn’t feel like a silk sonic song but rather an Anderson .Paak song ft. Bruno Mars. 777 sounded just too stupid for me.

However, Put on a smile reminded me of the amazing solo songs that early Bruno Mars made like grenade which was beautiful. After last night was also a great song although I thought there was gonna be a beat switch when the synths build but it goes back to the normal song.

I also think that the album is telling a story the way that it is sequenced. Leave the door open is them meeting the girl, fly as me is them asking the girl to natch their energy. After last night is them falling in love with the girl, smokin out the window is them getting fed up with the girl and leaving, put on a smile is the, regretting their decision to leave, 777 is them gambling the pain away, skate is them starting all over again with a new girl.

I will admit though that it would make more sense if Leave the door open was before fly as me, and that the outro is kinda just a song about getting high.

I would say the album kinda disappointed me with how short it was and 2 new lackluster songs out of 5. However, the good songs are really really good.

Song rankings:
1. Put on a smile 10/10
2. Smokin out the window 10/10
3. Skate 10/10
4. Leave the door open 9/10
5. Blast off 9/10
6. After last night 8/10
7. Fly as me 6/10
8. Silk sonic intro (it’s a funky intro)
9. 777 4/10

Overall: Light to decent 8/10 in my opinion

textDisplay: I actually agree with Fantano here, which is rare,  but i felt the album just had uninspiring vocal & instrumental highs and lows that don’t contribute to the music in a meaningful way. The styles, vocals and instruments veneer into a blur, with all of them sounding like extensions of each other, which is a compliment for a single song, but a disappointment for a full album. It makes all the tracks undistinguishable from each other, and Bruno & Anderson felt to me interchangeable with each other, instead of each contributing from their strengths, they melted into each other and it felt nothing stood out. Basically the whole album felt like an AI put a 70’s soul and funk filter on 9 different songs, snd even though i did enjoy some tracks, ultimately they leave more to be desired.

textDisplay: Disappointing but… not surprised lol. I love that you feel so much love for experimentation and innovation in music, but I think it puts you and other album reviewers like the Pitchfork reviewers a bit out of touch. What I love so much about this record, and what I think younger generations love so much about this record, is that to us this weirdly feels fresh? Is it particularly innovative or a reinvention of the wheel? No, but I think that taking a genre that our generation generally perceives as stale and making it so relatable to us in a way that we haven’t experienced before is something we never could’ve imagined. That’s a feat to be admired. The establishment of genre is often the thing that causes its death, and this is because you can only innovate within a genre so much before making a new genre. What Silk Sonic has done so well here is take the idea of a genre that has been mostly left behind and written off, and show how much life and energy they can pull out of it, all while showing that musicians really can develop and create within the boundaries of a genre without renovating the genre itself. And don’t get me wrong, I love when people can take genres and turn them on their heads but what I can appreciate just as much is when a musician takes a genre, shows how much they love its form, and presents an analysis of the energy of the genre. Art is so imitative, not only of life but also of itself, and it takes a particular kind of musical talent to be able to imitate art of the past in one’s own voice and with their own mind. Not only that, but so much of music as a medium is based in the way it is performed, and within an audience’s ability to recognize the strength of a musician’s performance regardless of their own experience in music, and what Silk Sonic is able to do in this album both creatively and performatively is unmatched. While not particularly cutting-edge, the album is revolutionary in the way its swagger and musical fortitude have reignited an adoration for a dead genre in younger people. A musician does not need to be avant-garde to be impactful. I think what music reviewers have done is intertwine experimentation with musicianship, when in reality music is so much more than the next big thing, the next new idea.

textDisplay: One of my albums (or extra long EP!) of the year . Even with it's flaws it endears itself to the listener. textDisplay: Interesting that he didn't touch on the album's narrative from front to back, which I feel adds a lot to its appeal beyond being a 70's funk/soul cosplay. Getting into a relationship, letting your ego get a hold of you and ruin it, you lament, you find someone else/get back with that person from before, rinse and repeat, and I'm finding that the 30 min run time actually adds to the appeal of that, like going quickly in and out of relationships with the range of emotions/sentiments that it brings (albeit performed with a lot of charisma). It was the narrative and it's cyclical nature that I found to be the most appealing and deeply human and relevant with hookup culture.
textOriginal: Interesting that he didn't touch on the album's narrative from front to back, which I feel adds a lot to its appeal beyond being a 70's funk/soul cosplay. Getting into a relationship, letting your ego get a hold of you and ruin it, you lament, you find someone else/get back with that person from before, rinse and repeat, and I'm finding that the 30 min run time actually adds to the appeal of that, like going quickly in and out of relationships with the range of emotions/sentiments that it brings (albeit performed with a lot of charisma). It was the narrative and it's cyclical nature that I found to be the most appealing and deeply human and relevant with hookup culture.

textDisplay: It’s hard to call this album “soulful.” Silk Sonic lacks the sort of grit or dirtiness that you would normally associate with funk and soul records of the 70s. Silk Sonic is perhaps a little too pristine to be considered “soulful.” If I’m being completely honest… it feels more like 90s R&B. Silk Sonic probably falls under the same umbrella of “insubstantial” R&B music that prompted artists like D’Angelo, Lauryn Hill, and Erykah Badu to usher in a new era of soul and R&B music from the late 90s to early 00s.
textOriginal: It’s hard to call this album “soulful.” Silk Sonic lacks the sort of grit or dirtiness that you would normally associate with funk and soul records of the 70s. textDisplay: I'm not entirely surprised by your take here, but I do think some of the points are slightly askew. For example, you mention that the song 777 sounds like a James Brown song, which is quite easy to pick up, but they do cleverly reference that in the line "Papa need a brand new foreign" which alludes to James Brown's song "Papa's got a brand new bag", a song that is generally considered to be fundamental for the development of Funk. The album is obviously heavily inspired by 70's soul and funk but I dont think an album needs to be revolutionary in musical style to be fantastic, as long as the influences are referenced tastefully, which I think most would agree, they are. Influences aside the quality of the album is astounding. You mention that the instrumental palate is not varied but you can also argue that the album as a consequence is more cohesive. The "narrow" instrumental palate is accounted for by the length of the album which is more or less spot on. The lyrics aren't overly complex but I don't think that was ever the standout for soul and funk albums, most importantly, the lyrics convey what they need to effectively with a great sense of humor and personality. Lastly, I think you missed out on the sequencing of the song which tell a little cute story about falling in and out of love - of course, its not a cutting-edge concept album by any stretch of the imagination. Overall, I think the review is fair despite my grievances with the review (and it's just opinion at the end of the day). On a serious note, I'm deeply disappointed in the acute lack of a thread on your head in this video, 2/10.

The album is obviously heavily inspired by 70's soul and funk but I dont think an album needs to be revolutionary in musical style to be fantastic, as long as the influences are referenced tastefully, which I think most would agree, they are. textDisplay:
This album is paying homage, not ripping off the classic sounds of soul. The album is channeling the foundational musical legends of the 70s through two artists in their prime, two artists who owe everything to those legends and who know it and who SHOW it. The album is definitely short, but there's no filler. It doesn't strive ''modernize'' the sounds of soul, but I think they show other modern artists that great art can be made when you look back at where you came from. This album is definitely candy for the ears but it also made me think about how much I owe to the people in my past, to figures in history, in Black history, who live through every aspect of our culture today. I felt like dancing the whole time, I felt like celebrating and I was so grateful for the of legacy soul and R & B that moves me and consistently gets me through the day.

This album is a classic. 10/10 for me.

I think your score is interesting though. I can see how the brevity of the album can be held against it but I also think that your score shows that you prioritize ''inventiveness'' or ''originality'' in your critiques. I usually don't disagree with that prioritization because originality and inventiveness usually are the mark of an artist being truthful to themselves and their audience, showing a respect for their craft, etc. All individuals are unique, so all truthful expression of individuality will come out somewhat original and I find that interesting to listen . But in this case I see and feel it differently. Silk Sonic expressed their individuality by truthfully showing reverence to those that came before them, by embracing collaboration and by letting themselves just have fun and feel joy fully, no cynicism. Right now, culturally, that IS original. That is bold. In certain contexts, it takes a lot of inventiveness to let loose and have fun. In certain contexts, there is a lot of power in celebration.

It doesn't strive ''modernize'' the sounds of soul, but I think they show other modern artists that great art can be made when you look back at where you came from. This album is definitely candy for the ears but it also made me think about how much I owe to the people in my past, to figures in history, in Black history, who live through every aspect of our culture today. I felt like dancing the whole time, I felt like celebrating and I was so grateful for the of legacy soul and R & B that moves me and consistently gets me through the day. 

This album is a classic. 10/10 for me.

I think your score is interesting though. I can see how the brevity of the album can be held against it but I also think that your score shows that you prioritize ''inventiveness'' or ''originality'' in your critiques. I usually don't disagree with that prioritization because originality and inventiveness usually are the mark of an artist being truthful to themselves and their audience, showing a respect for their craft, etc. All individuals are unique, so all truthful expression of individuality will come out somewhat original and I find that interesting to listen . textDisplay: I personally felt a little disappointed on the first listen, as my three favorite tracks were the three already released as singles, but as a whole I loved it. I thought it was a fun throwback to the 70's. I thought that Bruno and Anderson had fantastic vocal chemistry. I thought that Blast Off was a beautiful way to end the record, and I think that a short 31 minute was better for the record, I think if it went longer it would have gotten stale, but i think it had a perfect runtime, and was able to stay enjoyable and excellent throughout. I thought it was a fun throwback.
textOriginal: I personally felt a little disappointed on the first listen, as my three favorite tracks were the three already released as singles, but as a whole I loved it. I thought it was a fun throwback to the 70's. I thought that Bruno and Anderson had fantastic vocal chemistry. I thought that Blast Off was a beautiful way to end the record, and I think that a short 31 minute was better for the record, I think if it went longer it would have gotten stale, but i think it had a perfect runtime, and was able to stay enjoyable and excellent throughout. I thought it was a fun throwback.
